docs.abstract: The extended F.B.I. investigation wasn’t what Republicans wanted, but it could end up easing the way for Judge Brett M. Kavanaugh’s Supreme Court confirmation.
docs.snippet: The extended F.B.I. investigation wasn’t what Republicans wanted, but it could end up easing the way for Judge Brett M. Kavanaugh’s Supreme Court confirmation.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — At first blush, Senator Jeff Flake’s last-minute decision to force a new F.B.I. investigation into accusations that Judge Brett M. Kavanaugh sexually assaulted a teenage girl when they were both in high school appeared to be a disaster for Republicans.

headline.main: How Jeff Flake May Have Saved Republicans From Themselves
headline.print_headline: How a Senator  May Have Saved  The Republicans

docs.abstract: In his presidential run, Mr. Trump said his Republican primary opponents would cut older Americans’ benefits. In this year’s elections, he has directed the same attacks at Democrats.
docs.snippet: In his presidential run, Mr. Trump said his Republican primary opponents would cut older Americans’ benefits. In this year’s elections, he has directed the same attacks at Democrats.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — President Trump had a blunt message for Montana voters last week, an unapologetic reprise of the promise to protect Medicare and Social Security that he used during the 2016 presidential campaign to successfully appeal to older, blue-collar voters.

headline.main: Taking Page From 2016, Trump Claims Democrats Will Destroy Safety Net
headline.print_headline: Promise and Policy Conflict On Entitlement Programs

docs.abstract: The bar association on three occasions gave Judge Brett M. Kavanaugh its highest rating. In 2006, though, after scores of interviews, it had doubts.
docs.snippet: The bar association on three occasions gave Judge Brett M. Kavanaugh its highest rating. In 2006, though, after scores of interviews, it had doubts.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — When Brett M. Kavanaugh was preparing for his second confirmation hearing for a seat on a federal appeals court in 2006, he got some unwelcome news. The American Bar Association, which had earlier given him its highest rating, had reconsidered.

headline.main: Bar Association Questioned Kavanaugh’s Temperament and Honesty in 2006
headline.print_headline: Bar Association Revised Rating of Judge in 2006

docs.abstract: Wearing a “Make America Great Again” hat to what was ostensibly a working lunch to discuss sentencing reform and other issues, Mr. West delivered a 10-minute soliloquy to the president.
docs.snippet: Wearing a “Make America Great Again” hat to what was ostensibly a working lunch to discuss sentencing reform and other issues, Mr. West delivered a 10-minute soliloquy to the president.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — After a week of extensive interviews, repetitive rally speeches and a torrent of tweets, President Trump, a fan of a good media spectacle, temporarily ceded the glare of the spotlight on Thursday to someone even more comfortable with it: Kanye West.

headline.main: Kanye West’s White House Rant Steals Trump’s Spotlight
headline.print_headline: Just Call Them Donye: An Oval Office Confab Gets Weird

docs.abstract: The announcement appeared to be part of a strategy to ramp up pressure against Beijing while also curbing China’s ambition to project its military power globally.
docs.snippet: The announcement appeared to be part of a strategy to ramp up pressure against Beijing while also curbing China’s ambition to project its military power globally.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The Trump administration announced on Thursday that it would sharply restrict exports of civilian nuclear technology to China that officials claimed was being diverted to power new generations of Chinese submarines, aircraft carriers and floating nuclear power plants.

headline.main: U.S. Puts New Restrictions on Nuclear Technology Exports to China
headline.print_headline: U.S. Adding Limits on Nuclear Technology Exports to China

docs.abstract: An Op-Ed column by an unnamed senior administration official added to the impression left by Bob Woodward’s book of aides seeking to thwart a president’s “reckless decisions.”
docs.snippet: An Op-Ed column by an unnamed senior administration official added to the impression left by Bob Woodward’s book of aides seeking to thwart a president’s “reckless decisions.”
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — President Trump sought to assert command of his administration on Wednesday amid reports of a “quiet resistance” among some of his own advisers who have secretly and deliberately tried to thwart from the inside what one official called his “reckless decisions.”

headline.main: Trump Lashes Out After Reports of ‘Quiet Resistance’ by Staff
headline.print_headline: Trump Seethes As a ‘Resistance’ Spills Into View

byline.original: By Peter Baker and Maggie Haberman

docs.abstract: The American military in Kabul was publicizing the number of killed enemy fighters. The propaganda tactic with echoes of the Vietnam War was stopped on Thursday.
docs.snippet: The American military in Kabul was publicizing the number of killed enemy fighters. The propaganda tactic with echoes of the Vietnam War was stopped on Thursday.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Taking a page from Vietnam War propaganda, the American military in Afghanistan has been widely publicizing body counts of Taliban and Islamic State fighters killed in battle. Officials described the practice, which began in January, as part of an apparent strategy to rally White House support for remaining in the conflict.

headline.main: U.S. Retreats on Publicizing Body Count of Militants Killed in Afghanistan
headline.print_headline: U.S. Retreats on Publishing Body Count of Militants Killed in Afghanistan

docs.abstract: The administration warned of a response to strikes in Iraq even as it moved to avoid a public split with allies over President Trump’s withdrawal from the nuclear deal.
docs.snippet: The administration warned of a response to strikes in Iraq even as it moved to avoid a public split with allies over President Trump’s withdrawal from the nuclear deal.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The Trump administration has signaled a new phase in its confrontation with Iran, threatening to retaliate for attacks by Iranian-backed militants in Iraq, even as it moves to avoid a potentially messy public split with allies over President Trump’s withdrawal from the nuclear deal.

headline.main: White House Threatens Iran With Retaliation Over Militant Attacks
headline.print_headline: White House Threatens A Response to Attacks By Iran-Backed Groups

docs.abstract: President Trump plans to take $20 million in foreign assistance funds and use it to help Mexico deport as many as 17,000 people in a bid to slow crossings into the United States.
docs.snippet: President Trump plans to take $20 million in foreign assistance funds and use it to help Mexico deport as many as 17,000 people in a bid to slow crossings into the United States.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — President Trump has promised for years that Mexico would pay for a vast border wall, a demand that country has steadfastly refused. Now, in the Trump administration’s campaign to stop illegal immigration, the United States plans instead to pay Mexico.

headline.main: U.S. Plans to Pay Mexico to Deport Unauthorized Immigrants There
headline.print_headline: $20 Million In U.S. Aid For Mexico Deportations

byline.original: By Gardiner Harris and Julie Hirschfeld Davis

docs.abstract: Secretary of State Mike Pompeo said the further cuts to an already scaled-back program reflected a “daunting operational reality.”
docs.snippet: Secretary of State Mike Pompeo said the further cuts to an already scaled-back program reflected a “daunting operational reality.”
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — President Trump plans to cap the number of refugees that can be resettled in the United States next year at 30,000, his administration announced on Monday, further cutting an already drastically scaled-back program that offers protection to foreigners fleeing violence and persecution.

headline.main: Trump to Cap Refugees Allowed Into U.S. at 30,000, a Record Low
headline.print_headline: Trump Plans to Cap Refugees Allowed Into U.S. at 30,000, a Record Low
